WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.160
Welcome, I'm Lou Bajic from RStudio.

00:00:08.160 --> 00:00:14.160
Thanks for joining this on-demand webinar on architecting RStudio products in the cloud.

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:20.240
Today we'll have a couple of people from our great partner Procogia, Oisin Bates and Kevin

00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:23.680
Bolger who will be presenting on this topic.

00:00:23.680 --> 00:00:29.980
This recording is a companion to our recorded webinar on what does it mean to do data science

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:30.980
in the cloud.

00:00:30.980 --> 00:00:35.220
If you'd like a bigger introduction to the subject before diving into the details here,

00:00:35.220 --> 00:00:37.500
I encourage you to listen to that first.

00:00:37.500 --> 00:00:42.540
If you have any questions after the webinar, any technical questions, please go to community.rstudio.com.

00:00:42.540 --> 00:00:45.660
We'll have a thread there to answer questions.

00:00:45.660 --> 00:00:50.740
If you have any questions about RStudio products or Procogia services, please contact sales

00:00:50.740 --> 00:00:55.020
at rstudio.com or outreach at procogia.com.

00:00:55.020 --> 00:00:56.900
And with that, I'll hand it off to Kevin and Oisin.

00:01:00.500 --> 00:01:09.500
Thank you, Lou, and welcome to this webinar on architecting RStudio products in the cloud.

00:01:09.500 --> 00:01:15.500
And just a quick introduction to our two presenters, there is myself, Kevin Bolger, I'm the director

00:01:15.500 --> 00:01:21.820
of data science at Procogia, and we also have Oisin Bates who's going to be talking us through

00:01:21.820 --> 00:01:31.419
some of the technicalities of architecting for RStudio products in the cloud.

00:01:31.419 --> 00:01:37.339
Just to give a quick overview of how the presentation is structured, first I want to give a quick

00:01:37.339 --> 00:01:44.919
introduction and overview of Procogia, what we do and how we work with RStudio.

00:01:44.919 --> 00:01:50.059
Then I'll give a brief overview of how we tackle working with companies that want to

00:01:50.059 --> 00:01:56.379
get RStudio Teams integrated on their cloud platforms, some of the business considerations

00:01:56.379 --> 00:02:01.199
that go on there, and also some of the requirements that we look to gather when we're trying to

00:02:01.199 --> 00:02:05.459
architect the ideal solution for our customers.

00:02:05.459 --> 00:02:12.619
And then I will pass it over to Oisin, and Oisin will talk about the more technical intricacies

00:02:12.619 --> 00:02:17.399
of architecting that solution for RStudio Teams environments and the different solutions

00:02:17.399 --> 00:02:21.880
that customers can deploy in the cloud.

00:02:21.880 --> 00:02:28.119
And after that, we will just close up the presentation and give out some useful links

00:02:28.119 --> 00:02:32.320
for people to investigate in their own time.

00:02:32.320 --> 00:02:37.240
So to start with Procogia, who are we and what do we do?

00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:42.679
Taking this from our company's mission statement, we empower organizations to achieve sustainable

00:02:42.679 --> 00:02:44.960
advantage through their data.

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:49.399
And we do this by enabling our clients to make more strategic and intelligent decisions

00:02:49.399 --> 00:02:53.160
on their data to implement their solutions.

00:02:53.160 --> 00:02:57.960
And we do this with the help of a diverse team of motivated team players who love what

00:02:57.960 --> 00:03:02.139
they do in data science.

00:03:02.139 --> 00:03:07.160
We follow a pretty standard framework for how we implement our solutions and we provide

00:03:07.160 --> 00:03:12.559
services end-to-end in the data journey, from advising clients who are just getting

00:03:12.559 --> 00:03:19.160
started with their data journey to helping them set up their ETL workflows and data warehouses,

00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:24.380
to reporting on that data and helping to understand the value that they can drive from that.

00:03:24.380 --> 00:03:27.919
And finally, helping them with some prescriptive and predictive analytics once they become

00:03:27.919 --> 00:03:32.679
a little bit more sophisticated and understand the kind of outcomes they want to get from

00:03:32.679 --> 00:03:35.639
their data.

00:03:35.639 --> 00:03:41.500
This can be broadly defined as following the IDOT framework, which looks at first designing

00:03:41.500 --> 00:03:47.160
your infrastructure to set up for proper data analysis, performing your data analysis in

00:03:47.160 --> 00:03:54.720
the diagnosis phase, optimizing then by using some more advanced predictive analytics, and

00:03:54.720 --> 00:04:02.740
finally using prognosis step to venture into prescriptive analytics, where we seek to provide

00:04:02.740 --> 00:04:11.740
guidance on how companies can change decisions to affect the outcomes.

00:04:11.740 --> 00:04:17.940
And to stay on the topic of our cloud journey with RStudio, we follow a very similar approach

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:22.660
in our cloud transformation, again, consulting with our partners where they need it to give

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:26.380
them guidance on where they can go, helping them plan and architect those solutions when

00:04:26.380 --> 00:04:32.500
they need it, and setting up the infrastructure to do BI reporting and data science on top

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:35.380
of.

00:04:35.380 --> 00:04:38.920
And of course, then, we are full service partners with RStudio.

00:04:38.920 --> 00:04:43.380
What this means is we are licensed to resell RStudio professional products.

00:04:43.380 --> 00:04:49.019
And we also have a team of RStudio administrators and instructors who help work with our clients

00:04:49.019 --> 00:04:55.339
and work with different customers of RStudio to design and implement and deploy the RStudio

00:04:55.339 --> 00:05:00.579
team suite.

00:05:00.579 --> 00:05:01.579
Who is this webinar for?

00:05:01.660 --> 00:05:05.299
Well, if you're watching this webinar, you're most likely already familiar with the RStudio

00:05:05.299 --> 00:05:06.779
team environment.

00:05:06.779 --> 00:05:12.619
Maybe some of your employees or maybe you yourself use the software at work.

00:05:12.619 --> 00:05:16.579
But you want to understand how you can learn about deploying this in the cloud and what

00:05:16.579 --> 00:05:19.260
kind of benefits that might bring to your organization.

00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:24.579
And so that's what we're going to explore within this webinar.

00:05:24.579 --> 00:05:33.540
And so that brings us to our first segment of the presentation on RStudio for the cloud.

00:05:33.540 --> 00:05:37.380
And the first thing we always like to think about is, what are some of the business considerations?

00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:41.140
So what does your team look like and what kind of tools will they need?

00:05:41.140 --> 00:05:44.100
Because RStudio team is quite a diverse set of tools.

00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:50.940
Do they need them all, some of them, and what capacity and what control levels do they need

00:05:50.940 --> 00:05:51.940
it?

00:05:51.940 --> 00:05:58.779
So we'd like to use this analogy to hit home how we look at different teams and the role

00:05:58.779 --> 00:06:01.339
that RStudio team can play in that.

00:06:01.339 --> 00:06:07.000
And this is a very good analogy that a former Procogia employee and current staff member

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:12.700
of RStudio, Gagandeep Singh, developed for us for a presentation a little over a year

00:06:12.700 --> 00:06:13.700
ago.

00:06:13.700 --> 00:06:18.980
And it's looking at the Star Trek USS Enterprise team and how they can be considered an aspiring

00:06:18.980 --> 00:06:23.179
data-driven organization.

00:06:23.179 --> 00:06:28.619
So within the USS Enterprise, we've got the blue shirts.

00:06:28.619 --> 00:06:31.540
And these could be considered analogous to our data scientists.

00:06:31.540 --> 00:06:33.660
These are our logical thinkers.

00:06:33.660 --> 00:06:39.220
They seek to understand business problems, translate them into analytic questions, and

00:06:39.220 --> 00:06:45.279
perform data wrangling and analysis to try and build some sort of advanced use cases

00:06:45.279 --> 00:06:50.239
on the data, whether it be machine learning or building dashboards and reports for business

00:06:50.239 --> 00:06:51.600
users.

00:06:51.600 --> 00:06:57.559
So our blue shirts, or our data scientists, are very motivated by getting the most out

00:06:57.559 --> 00:07:03.600
of our data and using the most cutting-edge technologies and techniques to derive value

00:07:03.600 --> 00:07:07.200
for them.

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:09.000
Then we have our red shirts.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:13.399
And these are our MAD engineers, our DevOps engineers.

00:07:13.519 --> 00:07:17.679
And these play a very crucial role in a data-driven organization.

00:07:17.679 --> 00:07:23.119
They plan and develop and test and maintain all of our enterprise infrastructure.

00:07:23.119 --> 00:07:25.679
And they build our CICD pipelines.

00:07:25.679 --> 00:07:30.519
And essentially, these are the engineers, these DevOps engineers, who make sure that

00:07:30.519 --> 00:07:34.839
everything works the way it's supposed to work and that data-driven teams have the tools

00:07:34.839 --> 00:07:39.839
and technologies that they need to do their jobs most effectively.

00:07:39.839 --> 00:07:45.119
So DevOps engineers play a very crucial role in a data-driven team.

00:07:45.119 --> 00:07:48.000
Finally, we've got the gold shirts.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:54.079
And these are our managers, our analytic managers, our business managers.

00:07:54.079 --> 00:07:59.239
And these are the powers that be who run the organizations.

00:07:59.239 --> 00:08:03.519
And their role is to work with the different stakeholders and understand what are some

00:08:03.519 --> 00:08:09.200
of the business use cases that the data team can utilize their data for.

00:08:09.559 --> 00:08:13.480
How can they get timelines and allocate their data scientists effectively towards these

00:08:13.480 --> 00:08:19.880
and work with the different senior stakeholders to make sure that the data team is providing

00:08:19.880 --> 00:08:22.880
adequate value to the company.

00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:27.679
So again, all of these three different members play very important roles.

00:08:27.679 --> 00:08:33.760
But they also have very different considerations and very different prerogatives.

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:37.239
Then we talk about the blue shirts.

00:08:37.239 --> 00:08:40.599
These are people who want a lot of time to test models on their own computer.

00:08:40.599 --> 00:08:42.440
But how can I make it run faster?

00:08:42.440 --> 00:08:45.080
They want more compute power.

00:08:45.080 --> 00:08:49.159
They also hear over here, the DevOps engineers talking about stuff like Jenkins servers,

00:08:49.159 --> 00:08:51.039
but they don't know what that means to them.

00:08:51.039 --> 00:08:53.039
So they want some more context there.

00:08:53.039 --> 00:08:56.479
Why do I care about Jenkins?

00:08:56.479 --> 00:08:58.440
They'll hear about technologies and the grapevine.

00:08:58.440 --> 00:09:01.880
So they might hear about Kubernetes and how they can make and process their data faster.

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:05.960
But, you know, they're not trained on how to utilize that.

00:09:05.960 --> 00:09:10.520
And finally, they may be interested in a centralized data platform.

00:09:10.520 --> 00:09:15.359
They might want to work with and collaborate with people across their company and maybe

00:09:15.359 --> 00:09:21.440
even across many sites across the globe.

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:24.159
And how can they share their data?

00:09:24.159 --> 00:09:28.000
So these are some of the considerations that the blue shirts might have.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:33.799
As for our DevOps engineers, our red shirts, well, they want to make sure that they can

00:09:33.799 --> 00:09:37.640
provide as much assistance to the team as possible, but they don't really know what

00:09:37.640 --> 00:09:39.799
the data scientist needs.

00:09:39.799 --> 00:09:41.239
They're not trained data scientists.

00:09:41.239 --> 00:09:44.559
They don't know what are the best tools, the most effective tools and technologies for

00:09:44.559 --> 00:09:46.280
them.

00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:50.280
And they just want more time to be able to work on this and provide the most suitable

00:09:50.280 --> 00:09:56.679
tools to their data teams and making sure that nobody's complaining about lack of compute

00:09:56.679 --> 00:10:01.039
power.

00:10:01.039 --> 00:10:06.359
As for our gold shirts, they're obviously interested in how the team is perceived around

00:10:06.359 --> 00:10:08.280
the organization.

00:10:08.280 --> 00:10:14.039
So are my team able to deliver and work together effectively?

00:10:14.039 --> 00:10:20.080
Are they able to run and test their models effectively in a time sensitive manner?

00:10:20.080 --> 00:10:24.479
Are they able to use all the cutting edge technologies that our competitors are most

00:10:24.479 --> 00:10:26.960
likely using?

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:34.039
And probably a very common case is I don't really have the budget to add an engineer

00:10:34.039 --> 00:10:35.039
to my team.

00:10:35.039 --> 00:10:38.919
Can I make my teams work more independently without the need for adding a new data engineer

00:10:38.919 --> 00:10:42.239
to the team?

00:10:42.239 --> 00:10:46.239
So these are all very valid concerns, and these three players work together very well

00:10:46.239 --> 00:10:51.320
and very effectively, and they can do that with the current setup, but they're missing

00:10:51.320 --> 00:10:52.320
a command center.

00:10:52.559 --> 00:10:56.000
And this is really what's important, and this is what ties everything back together, this

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:57.000
command center.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:01.640
And that is what RStudio Team Suite does.

00:11:01.640 --> 00:11:07.799
So we've got the RStudio Server Pro where data scientists can work together and collaborate.

00:11:07.799 --> 00:11:13.880
We've got the package manager, which allows the DevOps team to control and make sure that

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:21.880
all of the business use cases or business restrictions are met.

00:11:22.440 --> 00:11:25.400
And we've got the RStudio Connect where the data scientists can publish their results

00:11:25.400 --> 00:11:28.760
and share them out with all the different stakeholders in a really effective manner.

00:11:28.760 --> 00:11:34.479
So it's a fully integrated environment that allows everybody to work together in a seamless

00:11:34.479 --> 00:11:35.479
way.

00:11:35.479 --> 00:11:42.159
So you might ask yourself then, why would I want to use the cloud?

00:11:42.159 --> 00:11:48.799
Why not just deploy this on a local environment in an on-premise server?

00:11:48.799 --> 00:11:52.760
So for those who are uninitiated with the cloud, I'll take it slow.

00:11:52.760 --> 00:11:55.760
There are some major benefits to using the cloud.

00:11:55.760 --> 00:12:01.840
One of the most cited use cases is that you get to pay as you go, or rather you only pay

00:12:01.840 --> 00:12:04.159
for what you need.

00:12:04.159 --> 00:12:09.320
You also lower your total cost of ownership, so you're not paying for massive overheads.

00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:17.219
You take a lot of the guesstimating out of your work, so you can plan scalable infrastructure.

00:12:17.219 --> 00:12:23.859
You can focus more on innovation as opposed to managing and maintaining expensive infrastructure.

00:12:23.859 --> 00:12:27.419
And you can utilize the global networks and the ever-expanding global networks of different

00:12:27.419 --> 00:12:31.659
cloud providers to make sure your teams across the globe can interact with each other.

00:12:31.659 --> 00:12:36.140
And this is very important for large data science teams that are spread out across many

00:12:36.140 --> 00:12:39.140
different sites across the globe.

00:12:39.140 --> 00:12:45.580
Diving a small bit deeper into the pay-as-you-go model, what does it mean?

00:12:45.580 --> 00:12:50.419
Well, you trade in that expensive and rigid on-premise hardware for more highly available

00:12:50.419 --> 00:12:56.460
cloud infrastructure, only paying for what you use, no more or less.

00:12:56.460 --> 00:13:03.179
And so many providers provide this model, and this means there's a very low or sometimes

00:13:03.179 --> 00:13:05.099
even no upfront cost.

00:13:05.099 --> 00:13:08.619
So with some service providers, you'll even get a free tier where you can experiment with

00:13:08.619 --> 00:13:12.539
the different services and see if they meet your needs.

00:13:12.539 --> 00:13:17.780
And you can follow this graph here, it kind of trays a very basic model of how cloud costs

00:13:17.780 --> 00:13:22.219
can compare to very strictly managed on-premise costs.

00:13:22.219 --> 00:13:28.140
So as demand rises for on-premise servers, the engineers will have new servers spin up

00:13:28.140 --> 00:13:32.859
over time, and then once demand drops, they'll have to drop down that demand and so on and

00:13:32.859 --> 00:13:35.539
so forth over time.

00:13:35.539 --> 00:13:39.020
So this obviously leaves a massive amount of delta.

00:13:39.020 --> 00:13:42.739
If you overestimate, you're obviously paying for more compute than you need.

00:13:42.739 --> 00:13:47.460
And if you underestimate, sometimes you won't have enough compute power to meet the demand.

00:13:47.460 --> 00:13:49.299
With the cloud, you don't have to worry about that.

00:13:49.299 --> 00:13:54.820
Everything is scalable, everything's automated, and it can always meet the demand as it's

00:13:54.820 --> 00:13:55.820
needed.

00:13:55.820 --> 00:14:02.140
And this is thanks to the great scale that cloud providers are able to provide.

00:14:02.140 --> 00:14:07.260
You lower your total cost of ownership, so diving a small bit deeper into this one, you

00:14:07.260 --> 00:14:13.059
can think of cloud providers as, like I said, being able to benefit from the massive scale

00:14:13.059 --> 00:14:16.900
of having millions of customers.

00:14:16.900 --> 00:14:22.020
And so you don't need to dedicate specialists to maintain on-premise infrastructure and

00:14:22.020 --> 00:14:26.059
replace broken parts and faulty parts.

00:14:26.059 --> 00:14:29.020
Cloud providers take care of this completely.

00:14:29.020 --> 00:14:33.940
So all you have to worry about is configuring your infrastructure.

00:14:33.940 --> 00:14:36.619
So cloud runs high volume, low margin business model.

00:14:36.619 --> 00:14:39.260
That means they're passing those savings on to you as well.

00:14:39.260 --> 00:14:44.539
So again, because of that scale, they can just achieve a cost efficiency that is pretty

00:14:44.539 --> 00:14:48.739
much impossible at a local environment level.

00:14:48.739 --> 00:14:51.500
So this drastically reduces the cost of ownership.

00:14:51.500 --> 00:14:57.299
And if you go to the link I have attached here, you'll see a diagram that just compares

00:14:57.299 --> 00:15:01.739
the costs between on-premise and in cloud.

00:15:01.739 --> 00:15:05.739
And you can think of it like an iceberg where you have the tip of the iceberg that many

00:15:05.739 --> 00:15:11.059
people see and compare and contrast the two, but with on-premise, there's a lot of stuff

00:15:11.059 --> 00:15:16.619
hidden beneath that iceberg.

00:15:16.619 --> 00:15:20.700
Going back to our previous chart where we can see the different costs and how you can

00:15:20.700 --> 00:15:25.020
be a bit more accurate with cloud, this is because we can take that guesstimating out

00:15:25.020 --> 00:15:26.020
of things.

00:15:26.020 --> 00:15:30.059
We can scale up and down our servers if we need larger machines or smaller machines.

00:15:30.059 --> 00:15:34.539
We can use clusters to scale out and in our resources as needed.

00:15:34.539 --> 00:15:39.979
So if we're using Elastic MapReduce, for example, if you have very large data.

00:15:39.979 --> 00:15:44.340
And you're not going to be ever left with underutilized idling infrastructure.

00:15:44.340 --> 00:15:48.460
Your infrastructure is going to be used 100% as you need it, so long as you configure it

00:15:48.460 --> 00:15:49.460
that way.

00:15:49.460 --> 00:15:58.539
So that leaves full control over to us and completely reducing that idling time to zero.

00:15:58.539 --> 00:16:03.580
And of course, not having to manage all that infrastructure and not having to pay massive

00:16:03.580 --> 00:16:10.059
overheads for large compute machines and clusters, it means we can focus more on innovation.

00:16:10.059 --> 00:16:16.099
And I've taken some inspiration here from a previous cloud presentation I saw.

00:16:16.099 --> 00:16:21.500
And what we see here is if we look at our on-premise, we have the ability to experiment

00:16:21.500 --> 00:16:22.500
a lot less frequently.

00:16:22.500 --> 00:16:28.140
And this is because the kind of clusters that we need to do really advanced experimentation

00:16:28.739 --> 00:16:32.619
are very expensive, not just to provision, but also to maintain.

00:16:32.619 --> 00:16:37.260
And we've got to have dedicated engineers monitoring the health status of these.

00:16:37.260 --> 00:16:42.979
So that means failure is quite expensive if we experiment and result in nothing.

00:16:42.979 --> 00:16:46.539
That's a lot of cost incurred for that experimentation.

00:16:46.539 --> 00:16:53.419
So as a direct result of this, many companies see less innovation occurring on their on-premise

00:16:53.419 --> 00:16:55.140
servers.

00:16:55.140 --> 00:17:00.940
However, contrast that with cloud and we can experiment very often again because of that

00:17:00.940 --> 00:17:06.819
low cost, because you can get started for virtually nothing and scale up and scale up

00:17:06.819 --> 00:17:09.420
your costs as needed.

00:17:09.420 --> 00:17:13.979
So because of that, because of the lower cost of failure, it means that more innovation

00:17:13.979 --> 00:17:14.979
can occur.

00:17:14.979 --> 00:17:17.339
You can try out more models.

00:17:17.339 --> 00:17:19.140
You can try out new and different services.

00:17:19.140 --> 00:17:24.339
If they don't work for you, you can move on.

00:17:24.540 --> 00:17:29.619
And finally, the last component that I think is really important for cloud infrastructure

00:17:29.619 --> 00:17:36.140
is it really makes maintaining global teams a lot easier.

00:17:36.140 --> 00:17:38.900
With the cloud, there's no need to limit yourself to one location.

00:17:38.900 --> 00:17:42.060
You don't need to set up multiple data centers across the globe.

00:17:42.060 --> 00:17:49.040
You simply take advantage of the cloud providers already existing infrastructure.

00:17:49.040 --> 00:17:54.640
This means we can combat latency by having duplicated versions of our infrastructure

00:17:54.640 --> 00:17:57.680
in many different regions.

00:17:57.680 --> 00:18:01.199
And setup time can be completely automated to ensure consistency.

00:18:01.199 --> 00:18:07.479
So if there's very strict requirements on how the infrastructure is to be set up, we

00:18:07.479 --> 00:18:14.040
can automate that using different scripts.

00:18:14.040 --> 00:18:18.920
So that's a little bit about some of the business considerations as to why you would use RStudio

00:18:19.800 --> 00:18:22.239
and why you might want to consider using it in the cloud.

00:18:22.239 --> 00:18:28.000
Next, I want to talk about how we gather some requirements, and this is just a brief overview

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.920
of that.

00:18:30.920 --> 00:18:36.319
And so we like to consider each component of the RStudio team family as separate components

00:18:36.319 --> 00:18:39.520
that require separate considerations.

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:42.280
